---

<Layout title="Employment Pass vs PR Salary: Net Pay Comparison in Singapore | SalaryCalculator.sg" description="Detailed comparison of take-home pay between Employment Pass holders and Permanent Residents in Singapore. Covers CPF impact, tax differences, and total compensation.">
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbSchema)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />

  <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="mb-8 text-sm text-gray-500">
    <ol class="flex items-center gap-2">
      <li><a href="/" class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">Home</a></li>
      <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mr-2"><a href="/guides/" class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">Guides</a></li>
      <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mr-2 text-gray-900 font-medium">EP vs PR Salary</li>
    </ol>
  </nav>

  <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-4xl mx-auto text-gray-700">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-6">Employment Pass vs PR Salary: Net Pay Comparison in Singapore</h1>

    <p>
      One of the most common questions among foreign professionals in Singapore is whether converting from an Employment Pass (EP) to Permanent Resident (PR) status will make them better or worse off financially. The answer is nuanced: PR status reduces your monthly cash take-home pay due to mandatory CPF contributions, but it increases your total compensation through employer CPF contributions and unlocks significant long-term benefits. This guide provides a detailed, numbers-driven comparison to help you understand exactly how EP and PR compensation structures differ.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">The Fundamental Difference: CPF</h2>

    <p>
      The single biggest factor that distinguishes an EP holder's pay from a PR's pay is the Central Provident Fund. EP holders are exempt from CPF entirely - no employee contributions and no employer contributions. PRs (from the third year onwards) contribute 20% of ordinary wages (capped at $6,800 per month) and receive employer contributions of 17%. This creates a significant difference in both cash take-home pay and total compensation.
    </p>

    <p>
      To understand the full picture, consider two professionals - Alex (EP holder) and Bala (PR, 3rd year onwards) - both aged 32 and earning a gross monthly salary of $8,000.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Monthly Pay Comparison: $8,000 Gross Salary</h2>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Alex (Employment Pass Holder)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Gross salary: $8,000</li>
      <li>Employee CPF: $0 (exempt)</li>
      <li>Employer CPF: $0 (exempt)</li>
      <li>Cash take-home (before tax): $8,000</li>
      <li>Total compensation: $8,000</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Bala (Permanent Resident, 3rd Year+)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Gross salary: $8,000</li>
      <li>Employee CPF: 20% x $6,800 = $1,360 (CPF is capped at OW ceiling)</li>
      <li>Employer CPF: 17% x $6,800 = $1,156</li>
      <li>Cash take-home (before tax): $8,000 - $1,360 = $6,640</li>
      <li>Total compensation: $8,000 + $1,156 = $9,156</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Alex takes home <strong>$1,360 more</strong> in cash each month. But Bala's total compensation is <strong>$1,156 higher</strong> because of the employer's CPF contribution, which goes into Bala's CPF accounts. Over a year, Bala accumulates $13,872 in employer CPF alone - money that Alex simply does not receive in any form.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Annual Take-Home Pay Comparison</h2>

    <p>
      Extending the comparison to a full year with a 1-month AWS bonus (13th-month salary) changes the picture further. Assume both earn $8,000 x 13 months = $104,000 gross annual income.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Alex (EP) - Annual Breakdown</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Gross annual: $104,000</li>
      <li>Total CPF deduction: $0</li>
      <li>Pre-tax cash: $104,000</li>
      <li>Estimated income tax (resident rates, with earned income relief only): approximately $4,345</li>
      <li>Net annual cash: approximately $99,655</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Bala (PR) - Annual Breakdown</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Gross annual: $104,000</li>
      <li>Employee CPF (OW): $1,360 x 12 = $16,320</li>
      <li>Employee CPF (AW on $8,000 bonus, capped): 20% x $8,000 = $1,600</li>
      <li>Total employee CPF: $17,920</li>
      <li>Employer CPF (OW): $1,156 x 12 = $13,872</li>
      <li>Employer CPF (AW): 17% x $8,000 = $1,360</li>
      <li>Total employer CPF: $15,232</li>
      <li>Pre-tax cash: $104,000 - $17,920 = $86,080</li>
      <li>Chargeable income (after CPF relief and earned income relief): approximately $104,000 - $17,920 - $1,000 = $85,080</li>
      <li>Estimated income tax: approximately $3,234</li>
      <li>Net annual cash: approximately $82,846</li>
      <li>Total value (cash + CPF): $82,846 + $17,920 + $15,232 = $115,998</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Alex takes home about <strong>$16,809 more in cash</strong> per year. But Bala's total compensation (cash + CPF savings) is worth approximately <strong>$16,343 more</strong> than Alex's. The CPF savings earn guaranteed interest (2.5% on OA, 4% on SA and MA) and can be used for housing, healthcare, and retirement - representing real, tangible value.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Tax Differences</h2>

    <p>
      Both EP holders and PRs who are tax residents (present in Singapore for 183+ days) are taxed on the same progressive scale. However, there is a key difference: PRs contribute to CPF, and those employee contributions qualify as a tax relief. Bala's CPF contribution of $17,920 directly reduces his taxable income, saving him over $1,000 in income tax compared to Alex, who does not have this deduction.
    </p>

    <p>
      PRs may also be eligible for additional tax reliefs not typically available to EP holders, such as NSman Relief (if they perform National Service obligations, which applies to male PRs who were granted PR before certain age thresholds). However, most tax reliefs are available to all tax residents regardless of citizenship status.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Comparison at Different Salary Levels</h2>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">$5,000 Monthly Gross</h3>
    <p>
      At $5,000 per month (below the OW ceiling), the full salary is subject to CPF. The EP holder takes home $5,000 in cash, while the PR takes home $4,000 ($1,000 CPF deduction). The employer contributes an additional $850 to the PR's CPF. The PR's total compensation is $5,850 versus the EP holder's $5,000 - a 17% advantage in total value.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">$15,000 Monthly Gross</h3>
    <p>
      At $15,000 per month (well above the OW ceiling), CPF is capped at $6,800. The EP holder takes home $15,000, while the PR takes home $13,640. The employer CPF is $1,156. The PR's total compensation is $16,156 versus $15,000 - an 7.7% advantage. Notice that the percentage advantage decreases at higher salaries because CPF is capped at the OW ceiling, meaning the employer CPF contribution is the same absolute amount regardless of how much above $6,800 the salary is.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">$25,000 Monthly Gross</h3>
    <p>
      At $25,000 per month, the same CPF cap applies. The EP holder takes home $25,000 and the PR takes home $23,640. The employer CPF remains $1,156. The PR's total advantage is only 4.6% in total compensation. For very high earners, the CPF benefit becomes proportionally smaller relative to total income, though the absolute dollar value remains significant.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Beyond the Numbers: Qualitative Benefits</h2>

    <p>
      The financial comparison only tells part of the story. PR status confers several non-monetary benefits that can have significant financial implications:
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>HDB housing:</strong> PRs can purchase resale HDB flats and use CPF OA funds for down payments and monthly mortgage repayments. Given that HDB flats are significantly cheaper than private property, this benefit alone can save hundreds of thousands of dollars over a lifetime compared to renting or purchasing private property as an EP holder.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>MediShield Life:</strong> PRs are covered by MediShield Life, Singapore's basic health insurance plan, with premiums payable from MediSave. This provides a layer of healthcare coverage that EP holders must purchase privately.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Children's education:</strong> PR children pay significantly lower school fees at government schools compared to international student fees. The savings can amount to tens of thousands of dollars per year per child.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Job security:</strong> PRs do not need to maintain a work pass and can change employers freely without reapplying for a pass. This provides greater career flexibility and bargaining power in salary negotiations.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Retirement savings:</strong> CPF provides a structured retirement savings vehicle with guaranteed returns (2.5% on OA, 4% on SA and MA, with additional interest on the first $60,000). For long-term residents, CPF can accumulate into a substantial retirement nest egg.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">The PR Transition: What to Expect</h2>

    <p>
      If you decide to convert from EP to PR, the CPF transition is graduated over two years. In PR year 1, the default rates are 5% (employee) and 4% (employer) for those aged 55 and below, resulting in a modest reduction in take-home pay. In year 2, rates increase to 15% (employee) and 9% (employer), which represents a more noticeable pay cut. From year 3, full rates apply at 20% and 17%.
    </p>

    <p>
      Many new PRs find the year 2 to year 3 transition the most challenging, as the employee CPF rate jumps from 15% to 20%. Planning ahead - building a cash buffer during your EP years or during PR year 1 - can help smooth this transition. Some employers also offer a one-time compensation adjustment to help new PRs adjust to the lower take-home pay, though this is not universal.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Making the Decision</h2>

    <p>
      The EP vs PR decision is ultimately about your long-term plans. If you intend to stay in Singapore for the long term, raise a family, and build a career here, PR status is almost always financially advantageous when you account for the full value of employer CPF contributions, housing benefits, healthcare coverage, and retirement savings. If you are in Singapore for a short-term assignment and plan to return to your home country within a few years, the immediate cash advantage of EP status may be more relevant.
    </p>

    <p>
      Use our salary calculator to model both scenarios with your actual salary and see the precise difference in take-home pay. Remember that the monthly cash difference is only part of the equation - the CPF savings, tax benefits, and access to subsidised housing and healthcare are real economic value that should factor into your decision.
    </p>

    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-4 not-prose">
      <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100 p-6 group">
        <summary class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          Do EP holders take home more than PRs earning the same salary?
          <span class="text-primary text-xl group-open:rotate-45 transition-transform">+</span>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          Yes, EP holders take home more cash each month because they have no CPF deductions. However, PRs receive employer CPF contributions (up to 17% of capped wages) deposited into their CPF accounts, making their total compensation higher even though the monthly cash amount is lower. For example, on an $8,000 salary, an EP holder takes home $8,000 but a PR takes home $6,640 plus $1,156 in employer CPF.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100 p-6 group">
        <summary class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          Is total compensation higher for a PR or an EP holder?
          <span class="text-primary text-xl group-open:rotate-45 transition-transform">+</span>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          For the same gross salary, total compensation is higher for a PR because the employer contributes up to 17% of wages (capped at the OW ceiling of $6,800) to CPF on top of the salary. An EP holder receives only the gross salary with no additional employer contributions. At $8,000/month, the PR's total compensation is $9,156 versus the EP holder's $8,000.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100 p-6 group">
        <summary class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          Should I convert to PR to earn more in Singapore?
          <span class="text-primary text-xl group-open:rotate-45 transition-transform">+</span>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          Converting to PR increases your total compensation through employer CPF contributions but reduces your monthly cash take-home pay. PR status also provides access to HDB housing (significantly cheaper than private property), MediSave healthcare coverage, subsidised children's school fees, and structured retirement savings. If you plan to stay in Singapore long-term, PR is generally more financially advantageous. For short-term stays, the EP's higher cash payout may be preferable.
        </p>
      </details>
    </div>

